Lab_DataCompression Testing Guide
Author: Jason Sommerville
Date: July 8, 2021

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
./print-encoding.o [-l]
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Prints the encoding in encoding.txt generated by common.s in a more human-readable format. Expects to find encoding.txt in the directory in which it's called.
Optional Argument:
	-l: if this option is not used, will print vertical separators between each word


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
./print-tables.o
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Prints the tables in tables.txt generated by common.s in columns. Expects to find tables.txt in the directory in which it's called.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
./decode.o [-e]
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Decodes the encoding in encoding.txt generated by common.s and prints it. Expects to find encoding.txt in the directory in which it's called.
Optional Argument:
	-e: prints the decoding without printing the size of the decoding and without adding a newline at the end
	
	

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Generating new test cases
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
To generate a new test file, copy-paste or write text into a .txt document. The text needs to have a number of characters that is 
divisible by 4, and your text cannot be longer than 1024 characters. You need to ensure that there are no invisible characters that may bring the 
document's size over the limit or make the size of your text not a multiple of 4. In order to do this, I would recommend using a text editor such as Notepad++ that allows you to view 
all characters, including newlines, nulls, etc. After turning on this setting, you may find characters at the end of your test file such as "CR", "LF", "NL", or "NUL" that should be removed.
